history.content: If you've taken 162, I thought it was about the same overall amount of work.  As for the material, it was actually much easier to follow than I thought it would be; Prof. Sen has a nice way of teaching, and the concepts aren't too bad.  Plus, I thought the class was paced very nicely.  Would definitely recommend.

children.subject:
There is a weekly written assignment (not coding), usually 3-5 questions based on lecture material.  These aren't too bad, and you can work on it with other people.

The first project is a short, straightforward warmup project.  Projects 2-5 are all part of one big project, which is to implement a compiler for the COOL programming language.  Each of these projects is one part of the compiler - lexing, parsing, semantic analysis, and then code generation.  Projects 2 and 3 weren't too bad, on average they probably take 10-25 hours.  Project 4 is a bit harder, at least 1.5 times the work of projects 2 or 3.  Project 5 is the longest and hardest, but we were given about 5 weeks to do it.  I would expect most people took at least 50 hours on it.

You do have the option to work with a partner on the projects; my perspective will be different, since I worked on the projects by myself.  Personally, I found the class to be easier than 162, but everyone will have a different opinion.

I will say though that the projects in this class are probably my favorite of the CS classes I've taken; at the end, you have written a full compiler than turns source code into machine language, which is pretty cool.  Even if you don't end up ever working on a compiler after you graduate, this class definitely gives you a much better understanding of programming and OO languages.
